We present human annotators with an image and ask them to write a question for one of the categories, where each category comes with its own, customised set of annotation instructions with some examples (see Appendix¬†¬ßD for details). For the conditional counting category, we ask them to provide the question and the correct number as the answer. This way, we can generate correct and incorrect answer options from templates to get a multiple-choice setup consistent with the other categories. For the ordering and trick categories, we ask the annotators to provide the question as well as four correct answers and four incorrect answers. We employ a similar setup for the culture category, but we require the annotators to be fluent speakers of the language the culture is approximated by. This ensures that they are familiar with the concepts shown in the image. The commonsense questions ask for the most plausible answer. We ask annotators to provide the question, a single, most plausible answer and three other plausible answers, and take the most plausible option as the single correct answer.777Since for VCR we consider the most plausible option as the correct answer, this category cannot be easily transferred into the scenario with multiple correct answers: i.e., the plausibility threshold that determines correct answers would be very subjective and we would expect humans to perform poorly on that task as well. Therefore, we skip the robustness test with multiple correct answers for VCR, cf. Table¬†1.

Final Dataset.
The final data statistics over different categories and setups are provided in Table¬†1. Unless stated otherwise, we always report the results on the test portion, for which the correct answers are not publicly available to prevent data contamination¬†Dong et¬†al. (2024). The validation portion, with the correct answers available, is intended for hyper-parameter tuning and local evaluation. Along with the final dataset, we also release the annotations from which we sample the setups shown in Table¬†1; this might enable creation of new robustness evaluations by other researchers as well, beyond the ones introduced in our work.

Varying the Sets of Answer Options. After collecting up to four correct and four incorrect options (see 3.3 before), we sample three sets of four options where each set has a single correct option. The challenge in this setup is to answer the same question correctly more than once and to identify different correct answer options (among varying incorrect options as well). We report accuracy over all three variations. This provides the worst-case performance of the model for ‚Äòunfortunate variations‚Äô of the data instances. Again, we provide the information that there is always a single correct answer as part of the prompt. We refer to this setup as Single-Correct Answer + Variations. Single-Correct Answer Setup.
The results for this setup are summarised in Table¬†2. They indicate that even the simplest multiple-choice scenario is challenging for the state-of-the-art VLMs, with ample room for improvement. Gemini Flash shows the highest scores on average, followed by GPT-4 and Idefics2 which achieves similar results with Out-Gen and Out-Log as Gemini Flash and GPT-4. However, Idefics2 fails completely with Out-JSON.

Across all models, categories as well as output formats, performance in this setup is notably below the previous scores in the basic setup (cf., Table¬†2). The gap is very substantial and this holds even for the conditional counting category, where the correct answer is always the same number, which only gets expressed with different templates (e.g., 3 versus there are 3, see some examples in Figure¬†1 again). For the other scenarios, the different variations can also provide different correct answers (e.g., a position relative to different objects in an image for the Ordering category), which also adds to task complexity. Absolute scores and gaps, as expected, also depend on the model and the chosen output format (e.g., Idefics2 has a smaller performance drop with Out-Log than with Out-Gen).

Robustness to Different Prompts.
We measure this by the standard deviation of the scores across three prompts, both in single-correct (see Table¬†2 again) as well as in multi-correct setups (see Table¬†7 in Appendix¬†B). In the single-correct setup, the differences in accuracy due to prompt variation range from 00 to 20.420.420.4, depending on other factors (i.e., the underlying model, category, output format). Gemini Flash, while reaching the highest average accuracy in most categories, at the same time tends to have a higher standard deviation than the other VLMs and is thus less robust to the chosen prompt. The highest standard deviation in this setup is with LLaVA 1.6 on conditional counting with Out-JSON.

Robustness to Output Formats. Further, based on the results from Tables¬†2-4, we observe that the performance of the VLMs varies substantially conditioned on the chosen evaluation protocol and the output format. As indicated before, Gemini Flash performs best with a JSON-formatted output (i.e., the Out-JSON variant), and it also suffers from inconsistent formatting with Out-Gen. Therefore, in order to investigate to what extent the detected lower performance is due to answer formatting not picked up by the manually defined post-processing regular expression (see ¬ß4.1), we randomly sample 50 answers that are labeled as incorrect, and find that only 3/50 of the questions are false negatives.

LLaVA 1.6 and Idefics2 are again completely unable to follow these output formats, which aligns with the previous observation concerning the JSON-formatted output. Gemini Flash struggles with the CSV format, whereas GPT-4 reaches peak scores with that format for 3/5 categories. We further observe substantial drops with Gemini Flash with the other two formats, while GPT-4 seems most robust when faced with the these three output formats, but again with drops compared to the previous three formats (the Prv column) from Table¬†2, except for CSV. In sum, these results further point to general robustness and instruction-following issues with all the VLMs in our evaluation and again emphasise the gap to expected human-level performance.

The results on the culture questions in the single-correct setup are notably higher than for other categories in the same setup, and this holds for all the models (cf., Table¬†2). This is partially due to our dataset construction protocol and a strict quality control stage: the culture category requires in-depth understanding of the target culture which is why it is difficult to come up with challenging questions that are relatively easy to answer for humans. However, our main finding related to this category concerns large performance drops (i) when we move from the standard, easiest single-correct setup of concurrent research in culture-aware VQA¬†Romero et¬†al. (2024); Liu et¬†al. (2024a) to the multi-correct setups (cf., Table¬†4) and (ii) when we ‚Äòstress-test‚Äô the VLMs across robustness aspects (cf., Tables¬†3, 4, Figure¬†3).

The trick questions are based on descriptions generated by Gemini and GPT-4 making the results of these models not comparable to other models in this category. The scores (cf., Tables¬†2 and 4) render this category challenging for the VLMs. The good results of Gemini are surprising given that the questions target mistakes in descriptions generated by Gemini and GPT-4, and warrant further investigation.

Inspired by the observations with human annotators, recasting the task in such a way might also be beneficial for VLMs. The results of this approach are presented in Table¬†5. First, we report notable improvements for all the VLMs when we recast the task into a series of binary classification subtasks. The largest gain is achieved with LLaVA 1.6, and recasting the task now also enables LLaVA and Idefics2 to operate in multi-correct setups (as the scores are not straight zeros due to the single-correct bias anymore). The downside of the binary approach is efficiency (and the corresponding cost) as answering a single question requires multiple LLM inference calls. Importantly, even with the achieved gains in this binary setup, there is still ample room for improvement with all the VLMs in the multi-correct setup. On average, for counting, ordering or culture less than a third of the questions is completely solved by the state-of-the-art VLMs.
When we compare the predictions of the binary approach to the Out-GEN, Out-LOG, or Out-JSON, we observe that the biggest difference is for the questions with zero or four correct answers. As illustrated by an example in Figure 2, Gemini Flash provides only one answer when presented with all options at once. However, it is able to identify that all four options are correct when they are presented as a binary classification problem.

Adding ‚ÄòAll‚Äô and ‚ÄòNone of the Above‚Äô as Answer Options?
Answering single-correct questions has four possible answers, the four provided options. On the other hand, multi-correct questions increase the possible answers to each subset of the four options, also including two special cases: (i) all of them, and (ii) none of them. As indicated by the results in Table¬†4, Idefics2 and LLaVA in particular struggle with providing answers that are not explicitly listed as options. We thus experiment with providing the additional options ‚ÄôAll of the above.‚Äô and ‚ÄôNone of the above.‚Äô directly to the models. The results of this experiment with Out-Gen are shown in Table¬†8 in the appendix.

Answering single-correct multiple-choice questions requires providing one of the given answer options. For multiple-correct questions there are more options than just the ones explicitly listed. It can also be a combination of them or none of them. To explore the impact of making these options more explicit we add the options None of the above and All of the above.
